            <title><![CDATA[Nintendo Switch 2 Camera Accessory Revealed, Releases Same Day As Console]]></title>
            <link>https://www.gamespot.com/articles/nintendo-switch-2-camera-accessory-revealed-releases-same-day-as-console/1100-6530549/?ftag=CAD-01-10abi2f</link>
            <guid>https://www.resetera.com/threads/nintendo-switch-2-camera-accessory-revealed-releases-same-day-as-console.1152171/</guid>
            <content:encoded><![CDATA[https://www.gamespot.com/articles/nintendo-switch-2-camera-accessory-revealed-releases-same-day-as-console/1100-6530549/?ftag=CAD-01-10abi2f<br/><br/><div id="readability-page-1" class="page"><p>
    <span data-nosnippet="">GameSpot may receive revenue from affiliate and advertising partnerships for sharing this content and from purchases through links.</span>
  </p><article itemscope="" data-type-id="1100" data-guid="1100-6530549">

            
            
  


        

  


        
        
              <section>

                  
          <div data-content-element-selector="p, .js-buylink-item-container" data-allowed-classes-selector="js-buylink-item-container">
                <p>Nintendo Switch 2 is attempting to streamline the process of connecting with your friends, thanks to the addition of a new C button that launches a chat interface. You'll also get a chance to have actual video chats with your friends, as the Nintendo Switch 2 Camera will launch alongside the console on June 5.</p><p>While we don't have a full specification list for the camera, it's designed to connect to your Switch 2 via a USB-C port. It'll then allow you and your friends to join webchats, negating the need to use the Nintendo Switch Online app on your phone. There also seem to be some in-game features that require the camera, including various mini-games in Mario Party Jamboree.</p><figure data-align="center" data-size="large" data-img-src="https://www.gamespot.com/a/uploads/original/1702/17023653/4469284-switch2camera%281%29.jpg" data-ref-id="1300-4469284" data-ratio="0.5625" data-width="1280" data-embed-type="image"><a href="https://www.gamespot.com/a/uploads/original/1702/17023653/4469284-switch2camera%281%29.jpg" data-ref-id="1300-4469284"></a><figcaption>Nintendo Switch 2 Camera</figcaption><img src="https://www.gamespot.com/a/uploads/original/1702/17023653/4469284-switch2camera%281%29.jpg"></figure><p>You'll need to have a Nintendo Switch Online membership to use GameChat. However, GameChat will have a brief open access period that allows everyone to try the feature for free. When using the camera feed, your screen will split into two sections--a large top portion showing your game and a smaller panel at the bottom showing your group's streams.</p><p>Expect to learn more about the Nintendo Switch 2 Camera in the coming days. For now, check out all the <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/switch-2-nintendo-direct-april-2025-all-the-biggest-announcements/2900-6391/" data-ref-id="2900-6391">biggest announcements</a> from the latest Nintendo Direct.</p>
  
                        
    
        
        
  
